WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Free Gift Cards and Tech Items with
Southwest Points: www.fairylandshop.me

2
00:00:42.276 --> 00:00:45.212
<i>[Bell Rings]</i>

3
00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:48.215
Why are you late? You're
not going to like the answer.

4
00:00:48.282 --> 00:00:50.649
I already know the
answer. I missed the bus.

5
00:00:50.717 --> 00:00:53.653
I don't doubt it. No
bus stops near Brad's.

6
00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:56.155
You spent the night. the alarm
didn't work— or maybe it did.

7
00:00:56.223 --> 00:00:58.658
I didn't sleep with him. Girl.
either there's something...

8
00:00:58.725 --> 00:01:00.660
I missed the bus!

9
00:01:00.727 --> 00:01:03.706
There's something either very wrong
with you or something very wrong with him.

10
00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:06.666
There's nothing wrong with him.
Please tell me you know that for a fact.

11
00:01:06.733 --> 00:01:08.668
Melanie. I gotta go.
You're lying. aren't you?

12
00:01:08.735 --> 00:01:12.069
I wouldn't lie to you.
Good morning. guys!

13
00:01:12.139 --> 00:01:14.074
[Class] Good
morning. Miss Rebecca!

14
00:01:14.141 --> 00:01:16.906
Everybody's in their seats? Yes.

15
00:01:18.345 --> 00:01:22.942
Okay. Sydney. why don't you
tell us what you did this weekend?

16
00:01:23.016 --> 00:01:24.951
<i>[Child] She look—</i>

17
00:01:25.018 --> 00:01:27.283
Come on. Sydney.
We know you're not shy.

18
00:01:27.354 --> 00:01:31.621
How come we always have to tell you what
we did. and you never tell us what you did?

19
00:01:31.692 --> 00:01:33.627
[Girls Giggling]

20
00:01:33.694 --> 00:01:35.595
Okay.

21
00:01:35.662 --> 00:01:37.756
<i>I had a really great weekend.</i>

22
00:01:37.831 --> 00:01:40.858
- But you can't tell
Miss Melanie. okay?
- What did you do?

23
00:01:40.934 --> 00:01:43.460
I made a new friend.

24
00:01:43.537 --> 00:01:46.473
It's so much fun to
make new friends. isn't it?

25
00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:48.008
Yeah. Yeah.

26
00:01:48.075 --> 00:01:50.772
Did you tell your mom and
dad about your new friend?

27
00:01:52.079 --> 00:01:54.014
Absolutely.

28
00:01:54.081 --> 00:01:57.108
You should never keep
anything from your parents.

29
00:01:57.184 --> 00:02:00.313
- And I told mine—
[Gibberish]
- [Class Laughs]

30
00:02:00.387 --> 00:02:01.980
[Chuckles]

31
00:02:02.055 --> 00:02:03.819
- Wha— - [Giggling Continues]

32
00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:08.893
[Gibberish Continues]

33
00:02:10.697 --> 00:02:13.064
Ca— Ba...

34
00:02:18.205 --> 00:02:21.471
Ha— Ba—Cra...

35
00:02:26.113 --> 00:02:30.551
C—A— L...

36
00:02:31.451 --> 00:02:33.977
<i>H— E— "The!"</i>

37
00:02:34.054 --> 00:02:35.920
<i>We know that word. "The."</i>

38
00:02:37.591 --> 00:02:39.253
- [Groans]
- [Gasps]

39
00:02:44.731 --> 00:02:46.666
[Groaning]

40
00:03:01.048 --> 00:03:03.984
<i>Twenty-nine-year old female.
First seizure one month ago.</i>

41
00:03:04.051 --> 00:03:07.351
<i>Lost the ability to speak.
Babbled like a baby.</i>

42
00:03:07.421 --> 00:03:09.754
<i>Progressive deterioration
of mental status.</i>

43
00:03:09.823 --> 00:03:12.759
<i>You see that? They all assume
I'm a patient because of this cane.</i>

44
00:03:12.826 --> 00:03:16.763
So put on a white coat like the rest of us.
I don't want them to think I'm a doctor.

45
00:03:16.830 --> 00:03:19.766
You see where the administration
might have a problem with that attitude?

46
00:03:19.833 --> 00:03:21.768
People don't want a sick doctor.

47
00:03:21.835 --> 00:03:24.771
That's fair enough. I
don't like healthy patients.

48
00:03:24.838 --> 00:03:28.434
The 29-year old female— The
one who can't talk? I like that part.

49
00:03:28.508 --> 00:03:31.103
She's my cousin.

50
00:03:31.178 --> 00:03:33.613
And your cousin
doesn't like the diagnosis.

51
00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:35.615
I wouldn't either.

52
00:03:35.682 --> 00:03:38.174
Brain tumor. She's
going to die. Boring.

53
00:03:40.587 --> 00:03:42.522
No wonder you're such
a renowned diagnostician.

54
00:03:42.589 --> 00:03:45.234
You don't need to actually know
anything to figure out what's wrong.

55
00:03:45.258 --> 00:03:48.194
You're the oncologist. I'm just
a lowly infectious disease guy.

56
00:03:48.261 --> 00:03:50.196
Yes. Just a simple
country doctor.

57
00:03:50.263 --> 00:03:52.698
Brain tumors at her
age are highly unlikely.

58
00:03:52.766 --> 00:03:54.962
She's 29. Whatever
she's got is highly unlikely.

59
00:03:55.035 --> 00:03:58.014
The protein markers for the three most
prevalent brain cancers came up negative.

60
00:03:58.038 --> 00:04:00.313
That's an H.M.O. lab.
Might as well have sent

61
00:04:00.337 --> 00:04:02.635
it to a high school kid
with a chemistry set.

62
00:04:02.709 --> 00:04:04.644
No family history.

63
00:04:04.711 --> 00:04:06.646
I thought your
uncle died of cancer.

64
00:04:06.713 --> 00:04:09.012
Other side. No environmental
factors. That you know of.

65
00:04:09.082 --> 00:04:11.449
And she's not responding
to radiation treatment.

66
00:04:11.518 --> 00:04:13.987
None of which is even
close to dispositive.

67
00:04:14.054 --> 00:04:18.856
All it does is raise one question:
Your cousin goes to an H.M.O.?

68
00:04:18.925 --> 00:04:22.123
<i>Come on. Why leave all
the fun for the coroner?</i>

69
00:04:22.195 --> 00:04:25.461
<i>What's the point of putting together
a team if you’re not gonna use them?</i>

70
00:04:25.532 --> 00:04:31.301
You've got three overqualified
doctors working for you. getting bored.

71
00:05:33.166 --> 00:05:36.034
<i>[Man] It's a lesion.</i>

72
00:05:36.102 --> 00:05:40.062
And the big green thing in the middle
of the bigger blue thing on a map...

73
00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:42.166
is an island.

74
00:05:42.242 --> 00:05:44.211
I was hoping for something
a bit more creative.

75
00:05:44.277 --> 00:05:47.941
Shouldn't we be speaking to the
patient before we start diagnosing?

76
00:05:48.014 --> 00:05:49.915
- Is she a doctor?
- No. but...

77
00:05:49.983 --> 00:05:52.295
- Everybody lies.
- Dr. House doesn't like
dealing with patients.

78
00:05:52.319 --> 00:05:55.255
Isn't treating patients
why we became doctors?

79
00:05:55.322 --> 00:05:58.258
No. Treating illnesses is
why we became doctors.

80
00:05:58.325 --> 00:06:01.591
Treating patients is what
makes most doctors miserable.

81
00:06:01.661 --> 00:06:04.927
So you're trying to eliminate the
humanity from the practice of medicine?

82
00:06:04.998 --> 00:06:08.560
If we don't talk to them. they can't
lie to us. and we can't lie to them.

83
00:06:08.635 --> 00:06:11.264
Humanity's overrated.

84
00:06:11.338 --> 00:06:15.384
- I don't think it's a tumor.
- First year medical school—if you hear
hoof beats. you think horses. not zebras.

85
00:06:15.408 --> 00:06:17.240
Are you in first year
medical school?

86
00:06:18.712 --> 00:06:22.342
No. First of all. there's
nothing on the CAT scan.

87
00:06:22.415 --> 00:06:24.350
Second of all.
if this is a horse.

88
00:06:24.417 --> 00:06:26.130
then her kindly family
doctor in Trenton makes the

89
00:06:26.154 --> 00:06:28.030
obvious diagnosis. and it
never gets near this office.

90
00:06:28.054 --> 00:06:30.649
Differential diagnosis. people.

91
00:06:30.724 --> 00:06:34.627
If it's not a tumor. what are the
suspects? Why couldn't she talk?

92
00:06:34.694 --> 00:06:38.096
<i>Aneurysm. stroke or some
other ischemic syndrome.</i>

93
00:06:38.164 --> 00:06:40.656
- Get her a contrast M.R.I.
- Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease?

94
00:06:40.734 --> 00:06:42.396
- Mad cow?
- Mad zebra.

95
00:06:42.469 --> 00:06:44.165
<i>Wernicke's encephalopathy.</i>

96
00:06:44.237 --> 00:06:47.105
No. Blood thiamine
level was normal.

97
00:06:47.173 --> 00:06:49.472
The lab in Trenton could have
screwed up the blood tests.

98
00:06:49.542 --> 00:06:53.172
I assume it's a corollary if
“people lie" that "people screw up."

99
00:06:53.246 --> 00:06:58.549
Redraw the blood tests and get her
scheduled for that contrast M.R.I. ASAP.

100
00:06:58.618 --> 00:07:00.951
Let's find out what kind of
zebra we're treating here.

101
00:07:12.632 --> 00:07:15.033
<i>[Woman On P.A.] Radiology.
please call the page.</i>

102
00:07:15.101 --> 00:07:17.297
<i>Radiology. please call the page.</i>

103
00:07:23.209 --> 00:07:25.838
I was expecting you in
my office 20 minutes ago.

104
00:07:25.912 --> 00:07:27.412
Really? Well. that's
odd because I had no

105
00:07:27.436 --> 00:07:29.258
intention of being in your
office 20 minutes ago.

106
00:07:29.282 --> 00:07:30.957
You think we have
nothing to talk about? No. I

107
00:07:30.981 --> 00:07:32.828
just can't think of
anything I'd be interested in.

108
00:07:32.852 --> 00:07:35.287
I sign your paychecks.
I have tenure.

109
00:07:37.624 --> 00:07:41.288
Are you gonna grab my cane now. stop
me from leaving? That would be juvenile.

110
00:07:46.733 --> 00:07:49.779
I can still fire you if you're not doing
your job. I'm here from 9:00 to 5:00.

111
00:07:49.803 --> 00:07:52.637
Your billings are practically
nonexistent. Rough year.

112
00:07:52.706 --> 00:07:55.642
You ignore requests for consults.
I call back. Sometimes I misdial.

113
00:07:55.709 --> 00:07:58.645
You're six years behind on
your obligations to the clinic.

114
00:07:58.712 --> 00:08:01.648
See? I was right. This
doesn't interest me.

115
00:08:01.715 --> 00:08:04.651
Six years times three weeks—
You owe me better than four months.

116
00:08:04.718 --> 00:08:07.210
It's 5:00. I'm going home.

117
00:08:07.287 --> 00:08:09.222
To what?

118
00:08:09.289 --> 00:08:11.281
Nice.

119
00:08:12.959 --> 00:08:16.896
Look. Dr. House. the only
reason why I don't fire you...

120
00:08:16.963 --> 00:08:19.899
is because your reputation is still
worth something to this hospital.

121
00:08:19.966 --> 00:08:23.198
Excellent. We have a point of
agreement— You're not gonna fire me.

122
00:08:23.269 --> 00:08:26.205
Your reputation won't
last if you don't do your job.

123
00:08:26.272 --> 00:08:29.436
The clinic is part of your
job. I want you to do your job.

124
00:08:29.509 --> 00:08:33.776
But. as the philosopher Jagger once
said. "You can't always get what you want."

125
00:08:41.554 --> 00:08:44.023
You're not my doctor.
Are you Dr. House?

126
00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:46.218
Thankfully. no. I'm Dr. Chase.

127
00:08:46.292 --> 00:08:48.227
Dr. House is the head
of diagnostic medicine.

128
00:08:48.294 --> 00:08:52.595
He's very busy. but he has
taken a keen interest in your case.

129
00:08:55.869 --> 00:08:58.566
We inject
gadolinium into a vein.

130
00:08:58.638 --> 00:09:01.422
It distributes itself throughout
your brain and acts as

131
00:09:01.446 --> 00:09:04.202
a contrast material for the
magnetic resonance imager.

132
00:09:05.378 --> 00:09:08.314
Basically. whatever's in your
head lights up like a Christmas tree.

133
00:09:08.381 --> 00:09:11.180
- It might make you feel
a little light-headed.
<i>- Dr. Cameron.</i>

134
00:09:11.251 --> 00:09:14.847
I'm sorry. I have to stop
you. There is a problem.

135
00:09:15.922 --> 00:09:17.447
You pulled my authorization!

136
00:09:17.524 --> 00:09:19.584
Yes. Why are you yelling?

137
00:09:19.659 --> 00:09:21.651
No M.R.I.'s. no
imaging studies. no labs.

138
00:09:21.728 --> 00:09:24.755
You also can't make
long distance phone calls.

139
00:09:24.831 --> 00:09:28.477
- If you're going to fire me.
have the guts to face me.
- Or photocopies. You're still yelling.

140
00:09:28.501 --> 00:09:31.369
I'm angry! You're
risking a patient's life.

141
00:09:31.438 --> 00:09:34.272
- I assume those are two separate points.
- You showed me disrespect.

142
00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:36.652
You embarrassed me. And as long
as I work here. you have no legal...

143
00:09:36.676 --> 00:09:38.611
Is the yelling
designed to scare me?

144
00:09:38.678 --> 00:09:43.116
Because I'm not sure what it is I'm
supposed to be scared of. More yelling?

145
00:09:43.183 --> 00:09:45.118
That's not scary.

146
00:09:45.185 --> 00:09:48.485
That you're going to hurt me? That's scary.
But I'm pretty sure I can outrun you.

147
00:09:50.523 --> 00:09:53.493
Oh. I looked into that
philosopher you quoted—Jagger.

148
00:09:53.560 --> 00:09:56.394
<i>And you’re right. you can't
always get what you want.</i>

149
00:09:56.463 --> 00:10:00.366
But as it turns out. "If you try
sometimes. you get what you need."

150
00:10:01.434 --> 00:10:04.404
So. because you want
me to treat patients.

151
00:10:04.471 --> 00:10:07.498
you're not letting
me treat patients?

152
00:10:07.574 --> 00:10:09.406
I need you to do your job.

153
00:10:11.244 --> 00:10:13.236
[Sighs]

154
00:10:18.685 --> 00:10:21.519
Do the M.R.I. She folded.

155
00:10:24.624 --> 00:10:26.979
I've got to do four
hours a week in this

156
00:10:27.003 --> 00:10:29.619
clinic until I make up
the time I've missed.

157
00:10:30.630 --> 00:10:34.863
2054. I'll be caught up in 2054.

158
00:10:35.935 --> 00:10:38.769
You better love this
cousin a whole lot.

159
00:11:12.639 --> 00:11:15.837
All right. Rebecca. I know you may
feel a little claustrophobic in there.

160
00:11:15.909 --> 00:11:18.140
<i>but we need you to remain still.</i>

161
00:11:19.145 --> 00:11:22.343
<i>[Chase] Okay.
we're going to begin.</i>

162
00:11:22.415 --> 00:11:24.714
[Machinery Clicking]

163
00:11:26.719 --> 00:11:30.087
[Thumping. Clicking Continues]

164
00:11:31.357 --> 00:11:34.122
I don't feel so good.

165
00:11:34.194 --> 00:11:36.789
<i>[Chase] It's all right. Just
try to relax.</i> [Loud Humming]

166
00:11:38.131 --> 00:11:42.398
[Gasping]

167
00:11:43.970 --> 00:11:46.462
- Rebecca?
- [Gasping Continues]

168
00:11:47.574 --> 00:11:49.566
<i>Rebecca?</i>

169
00:11:58.851 --> 00:12:01.286
Rebecca?

170
00:12:01.354 --> 00:12:03.755
Get her out of there. Oh.
she probably fell asleep.

171
00:12:03.823 --> 00:12:06.156
She's exhausted. She was
claustrophobic 30 seconds ago.

172
00:12:06.226 --> 00:12:08.068
She's not sleeping. We
gotta get her out of there.

173
00:12:08.092 --> 00:12:09.205
It'll just be another minute.

174
00:12:09.229 --> 00:12:10.905
If she's having an
allergic reaction to the

175
00:12:10.929 --> 00:12:12.589
gadolinium. she'll be
dead in two minutes.

176
00:12:14.367 --> 00:12:17.030
Hold her neck. All right.

177
00:12:17.103 --> 00:12:19.334
Oh. she's ashen.

178
00:12:19.405 --> 00:12:21.374
She's not breathing. Epi.5.

179
00:12:21.441 --> 00:12:23.774
[Oxygen Hissing] Come on.

180
00:12:23.843 --> 00:12:25.778
I can't ventilate.

181
00:12:29.249 --> 00:12:31.351
Too much edema. Where's
the surgical airway kit?

182
00:12:31.375 --> 00:12:32.375
<i>[Chase] Yep. Coming.</i>

183
00:13:08.154 --> 00:13:10.055
Good call.

184
00:13:12.058 --> 00:13:14.186
[Oxygen Pumping]

185
00:13:30.276 --> 00:13:33.610
<i>We'll get that tube out
of your throat later today.</i>

186
00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:36.377
Just get some
rest for now. okay?

187
00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:41.781
Told you. You
can't trust people.

188
00:13:41.854 --> 00:13:43.789
She probably knew she
was allergic to gadolinium.

189
00:13:43.856 --> 00:13:46.985
Figured it was an easy way to get
someone to cut a hole in her throat.

190
00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:49.928
Can't get a picture. Gonna
have to get a thousand words.

191
00:13:49.996 --> 00:13:53.524
You actually want me to talk
to the patient. get a history?

192
00:13:53.599 --> 00:13:55.887
We need to know if there's
some genetic or environmental

193
00:13:55.911 --> 00:13:57.934
cause that's triggering
an inflammatory response.

194
00:13:58.004 --> 00:13:59.939
I thought everybody lied.

195
00:14:00.006 --> 00:14:03.204
Truth begins in lies.

196
00:14:03.276 --> 00:14:05.268
Think about it.

197
00:14:06.579 --> 00:14:08.775
That doesn't mean
anything. does it?

198
00:14:12.685 --> 00:14:16.122
<i>12:52 p.m. Dr. House checks
in. Please write that down.</i>

199
00:14:16.189 --> 00:14:18.124
Do you have cable
TV here somewhere?

200
00:14:18.191 --> 00:14:20.126
<i>General Hospital</i>
starts in eight minutes.

201
00:14:20.193 --> 00:14:22.128
No TV. but we've got patients.

202
00:14:22.195 --> 00:14:24.630
Can't you give out the aspirin
yourself? I'll do paperwork.

203
00:14:24.697 --> 00:14:27.676
I made sure your first case was an
interesting one. Cough just won't go away?

204
00:14:27.700 --> 00:14:30.679
Runny nose looks a funny color? Patient
admitted complaining of back spasms.

205
00:14:30.703 --> 00:14:32.745
Oh? I think I read about
something like that in the

206
00:14:32.769 --> 00:14:34.834
<i>New England Journal of
Medicine.</i> Patient is orange.

207
00:14:34.907 --> 00:14:37.138
The color? No. the fruit.

208
00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:39.645
You mean yellow. It's
jaundice. I mean orange.

209
00:14:39.712 --> 00:14:41.908
Well. how orange? It's
probably— Exam room one.

210
00:14:41.981 --> 00:14:44.143
<i>[Woman On P.A.] Dr. Kahn.
you're needed in pediatrics.</i>

211
00:14:45.418 --> 00:14:50.220
I was playing golf and my cleats got stuck.
It hurt a little. but I kept playing.

212
00:14:50.289 --> 00:14:53.418
The next morning. I
could barely stand up.

213
00:14:53.493 --> 00:14:56.691
Well. you're smiling. so I take
it that means this isn't serious.

214
00:14:57.830 --> 00:14:59.924
What's that? What are you doing?

215
00:14:59.999 --> 00:15:01.900
Painkillers.

216
00:15:01.968 --> 00:15:04.870
Oh. for you. For your leg.
No. 'cause they're yummy.

217
00:15:04.937 --> 00:15:08.066
<i>You want one? Make
your back feel better.</i>

218
00:15:09.642 --> 00:15:12.544
Unfortunately. you
have a deeper problem.

219
00:15:12.612 --> 00:15:14.911
Your wife is having an affair.

220
00:15:14.981 --> 00:15:18.042
- What?
- You're orange. you moron.

221
00:15:18.117 --> 00:15:20.348
<i>It's one thing for
you not to notice.</i>

222
00:15:20.420 --> 00:15:22.392
but if your wife hasn't
picked up on the fact that her

223
00:15:22.416 --> 00:15:24.633
husband has changed colors.
she's just not paying attention.

224
00:15:24.657 --> 00:15:26.666
By the way. do you
consume just a ridiculous

225
00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:28.492
amount of carrots
and megados vitamins?

226
00:15:28.561 --> 00:15:30.321
<i>Carrots turn you yellow.
the niacin turns you</i>

227
00:15:30.345 --> 00:15:32.089
<i>red. Find some finger
paint and do the math.</i>

228
00:15:32.165 --> 00:15:34.100
And get a good lawyer.

229
00:15:34.167 --> 00:15:36.159
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

230
00:15:39.205 --> 00:15:41.140
Deep breath.

231
00:15:41.207 --> 00:15:43.733
It's cold.

232
00:15:43.810 --> 00:15:45.904
He's been using his inhaler?

233
00:15:45.978 --> 00:15:48.914
Not in the past few
days. He's. um. only 10.

234
00:15:48.981 --> 00:15:51.746
I worry about children taking
such strong medicine so frequently.

235
00:15:51.818 --> 00:15:54.720
What happened to your leg?

236
00:15:54.787 --> 00:15:57.780
Your doctor probably was concerned
about the strength of the medicine too.

237
00:15:57.857 --> 00:16:01.157
She probably weighed that danger
against the danger of not breathing.

238
00:16:01.227 --> 00:16:05.790
Oxygen is so important during those
prepubescent years. Don't you think?

239
00:16:05.865 --> 00:16:08.801
<i>Okay. I'm gonna assume nobody
has ever told you what asthma is.</i>

240
00:16:08.868 --> 00:16:11.235
Or if they have. you had
other things on your mind.

241
00:16:11.304 --> 00:16:14.832
A stimulant triggers cells
in your child's airways...

242
00:16:14.907 --> 00:16:18.469
<i>to release substances that inflame the
air passages and cause them to contract.</i>

243
00:16:18.544 --> 00:16:21.912
<i>Mucus production increases.
the cell lining starts to shed.</i>

244
00:16:21.981 --> 00:16:24.507
- But the steroids— - [Wheezing]

245
00:16:24.584 --> 00:16:28.248
<i>the steroids stop
the inflammation.</i>

246
00:16:29.522 --> 00:16:31.650
The more often this happens...

247
00:16:32.692 --> 00:16:34.354
What? The more often
this happens. what?

248
00:16:34.427 --> 00:16:38.421
Forget it. If you don't trust steroids.
you shouldn't trust doctors. <i>[Door Closes]</i>

249
00:16:38.498 --> 00:16:41.696
<i>My mother passed
away four years ago.</i>

250
00:16:41.767 --> 00:16:47.035
She had a heart attack. and my father
broke his back doing construction...

251
00:16:47.106 --> 00:16:49.371
<i>♪♪ [Pager]</i>

252
00:16:49.442 --> 00:16:52.435
It's House. It's
urgent. I'm sorry.

253
00:16:55.848 --> 00:16:58.579
You couldn't have knocked?

254
00:16:58.651 --> 00:17:02.679
Steroids. Give her steroids.
High doses of prednisone.

255
00:17:11.364 --> 00:17:14.801
You're looking for support for a
diagnosis of cerebral vasculitis?

256
00:17:14.867 --> 00:17:16.249
Inflammation of blood
vessels in the brain is

257
00:17:16.273 --> 00:17:17.679
awfully rare. especially
for someone her age.

258
00:17:17.703 --> 00:17:20.605
- So is a tumor. Her sed rate is elevated.
- Mildly.

259
00:17:20.673 --> 00:17:23.074
That could mean
anything. Or nothing.

260
00:17:23.142 --> 00:17:26.078
Yeah. I know. I have no
reason to think that it's vasculitis.

261
00:17:26.145 --> 00:17:28.080
Except that it could be.

262
00:17:28.147 --> 00:17:29.753
If the blood vessels are
inflamed. that's gonna look

263
00:17:29.777 --> 00:17:31.627
exactly like what we saw on
the M.R.I. from Trenton County.

264
00:17:31.651 --> 00:17:33.984
and the pressure is gonna
cause neurological symptoms.

265
00:17:34.053 --> 00:17:36.921
- We can't diagnose that without a biopsy.
- Yes. we can.

266
00:17:36.989 --> 00:17:39.254
We treat her. If she gets
better. we know we're right.

267
00:17:39.325 --> 00:17:42.693
- And if we're wrong?
- Then we learn something else.

268
00:17:47.500 --> 00:17:49.196
Why steroids?

269
00:17:49.268 --> 00:17:51.203
Just part of your treatment.

270
00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:53.068
You haven't had many visitors.

271
00:17:53.139 --> 00:17:55.233
No boyfriend? Three dates.

272
00:17:55.308 --> 00:17:58.608
I wouldn't have stood by
him if he were vomiting all day.

273
00:17:58.678 --> 00:18:01.011
What about work? You
must have friends from work.

274
00:18:01.080 --> 00:18:04.881
Pretty much everybody
I like is five years old.

275
00:18:06.185 --> 00:18:08.620
The nurse said you're
stopping my radiation.

276
00:18:09.989 --> 00:18:13.118
We're just trying some
alternative medication.

277
00:18:13.192 --> 00:18:16.560
So where's your family from then? Steroids
aren't an alternative to radiation.

278
00:18:16.629 --> 00:18:18.825
The tests weren't
really conclusive.

279
00:18:18.898 --> 00:18:20.833
We're treating
you for vasculitis.

280
00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.893
It's the inflammation of
blood vessels in the brain.

281
00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:26.906
I-It's not a tumor?

282
00:18:26.973 --> 00:18:28.965
I don't have a tumor?

283
00:18:32.244 --> 00:18:35.737
You should have told her the
truth— It's a long shot guess.

284
00:18:35.815 --> 00:18:38.250
Thank you. If House
is right. no harm.

285
00:18:38.317 --> 00:18:40.684
If he's wrong. I've given a dying
woman a couple days' hope.

286
00:18:40.753 --> 00:18:44.417
False hope. If there was any other type
available. I would have given her that.

287
00:18:49.862 --> 00:18:52.388
[Sniffing]

288
00:18:52.465 --> 00:18:56.266
<i>Why are you
smelling Billy's pants?</i>

289
00:18:56.335 --> 00:18:58.600
I'm not. Looked like you were.

290
00:18:58.671 --> 00:19:00.833
- I was smelling the floor.
- Oh.

291
00:19:00.906 --> 00:19:03.740
Do you have any
pets in this class?

292
00:19:03.809 --> 00:19:07.109
No. But we used to have a gerbil.
but Carly L. dropped a book on it.

293
00:19:07.179 --> 00:19:09.114
Careless.

294
00:19:09.181 --> 00:19:13.141
- Do you need to smell it?
- No. I'm smelling for mold.

295
00:19:13.219 --> 00:19:15.154
I don't need to smell it.

296
00:19:15.221 --> 00:19:16.751
You could smell our parrot.

297
00:19:16.775 --> 00:19:19.454
You said you didn't have
any pets in this class.

298
00:19:19.525 --> 00:19:21.517
A parrot is a bird.

299
00:19:21.594 --> 00:19:23.290
Listen. Jackson's
not the father...

300
00:19:23.362 --> 00:19:25.562
<i>[Foreman] Parrots are the
primary source of psittacosis.</i>

301
00:19:25.598 --> 00:19:27.294
It's not the parrot.

302
00:19:27.366 --> 00:19:32.270
And psittacosis can lead to nerve
problems and neurological complications.

303
00:19:32.338 --> 00:19:34.603
How many kids were
in the class? Twenty.

304
00:19:34.674 --> 00:19:37.109
How many are home
sick? None. but...

305
00:19:37.176 --> 00:19:40.085
None. But you figured
that five-year-olds are more

306
00:19:40.109 --> 00:19:42.808
serious about bird
hygiene than their teacher?

307
00:19:42.882 --> 00:19:44.962
<i>Have you been through her
home? She lives in Trenton.</i>

308
00:19:45.017 --> 00:19:48.215
I can go up to her room tomorrow
morning. ask her for the key.

309
00:19:48.287 --> 00:19:52.349
Would the police call for permission before
dropping by to check out a crime scene?

310
00:19:52.425 --> 00:19:54.180
It's not a crime scene.
As far as I know.

311
00:19:54.204 --> 00:19:56.157
she's running a meth
lab out of her basement.

312
00:19:56.228 --> 00:19:58.144
She's a kindergarten
teacher. And if I were a

313
00:19:58.168 --> 00:20:00.324
kindergarten student I
would trust her implicitly.

314
00:20:01.701 --> 00:20:05.661
[Sighs] Okay. I'll give
you a "for instance."

315
00:20:05.738 --> 00:20:07.639
<i>The lady back there...</i>

316
00:20:07.707 --> 00:20:10.142
who made your egg
salad sandwich...

317
00:20:10.209 --> 00:20:13.043
Her eyes look glassy.
Did you notice that?

318
00:20:13.112 --> 00:20:16.549
<i>Now. hospital policy is
to stay home if you’re sick.</i>

319
00:20:16.615 --> 00:20:20.313
But if you're making $8.00 an hour. then
you kind of need the $8.00 an hour. right?

320
00:20:20.386 --> 00:20:22.346
<i>And the sign in the
bathroom says that</i>

321
00:20:22.370 --> 00:20:24.824
<i>employees must wash
after using the facilities.</i>

322
00:20:24.890 --> 00:20:27.804
but I figure that somebody
who wipes snot on a sleeve

323
00:20:27.828 --> 00:20:30.488
isn't hyper concerned
about sanitary conditions.

324
00:20:30.563 --> 00:20:33.055
So what do you think—
Should I trust her?

325
00:20:34.133 --> 00:20:37.763
I want you to check the patient's home
for contaminants. garbage. medication.

326
00:20:37.837 --> 00:20:39.549
I can't just break
into someone's house.

327
00:20:39.573 --> 00:20:41.569
Isn't that how you got
into the Felkers' home?

328
00:20:46.178 --> 00:20:49.171
Yeah. I know.

329
00:20:49.248 --> 00:20:53.276
Court records are sealed. You
were 16. It was a stupid mistake.

330
00:20:53.352 --> 00:20:57.084
But your old gym teacher has a big
mouth. Should write a thank-you note.

331
00:20:57.156 --> 00:20:59.557
- I should thank him?
- Well...

332
00:20:59.625 --> 00:21:01.753
[Crunching]

333
00:21:01.827 --> 00:21:04.626
I needed somebody around
here with street smarts.

334
00:21:06.632 --> 00:21:10.364
Okay? Who knows when they're
being conned. knows how to con.

335
00:21:10.436 --> 00:21:12.029
I should sue you.

336
00:21:12.104 --> 00:21:15.302
Pretty sure you can't sue
somebody for wrongful hiring.

337
00:21:15.374 --> 00:21:20.074
But I'm pretty sure I can sue if you fire
me for not breaking into some lady's house.

338
00:21:32.691 --> 00:21:35.126
Doing research. People
are fascinating. aren't they?

339
00:21:35.194 --> 00:21:37.425
Why are you giving
Adler steroids?

340
00:21:38.964 --> 00:21:42.628
Because she's my patient. That's what you
do with patients— you give them medicine.

341
00:21:42.701 --> 00:21:44.636
You don't prescribe
medicine based on guesses.

342
00:21:44.703 --> 00:21:46.797
At least we don't since
Tuskegee and Mengele.

343
00:21:46.872 --> 00:21:49.808
You're comparing
me to a Nazi? Nice.

344
00:21:49.875 --> 00:21:52.071
I'm stopping the treatment.

345
00:21:56.715 --> 00:21:59.651
She's my patient.
It's my hospital.

346
00:21:59.718 --> 00:22:01.653
I did not get her sick.

347
00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:03.629
She is not an experiment.
I have a legitimate

348
00:22:03.653 --> 00:22:05.157
theory about what's
wrong with her.

349
00:22:05.224 --> 00:22:07.159
With no proof.

350
00:22:07.226 --> 00:22:08.159
There's never any proof.

351
00:22:08.227 --> 00:22:09.841
Five different doctors
come up with five

352
00:22:09.865 --> 00:22:11.789
different diagnoses based
on the same evidence.

353
00:22:11.864 --> 00:22:15.164
You don't have <i>any</i> evidence.

354
00:22:15.234 --> 00:22:18.534
And nobody knows anything. huh? Then
how is it you always think you're right?

355
00:22:18.604 --> 00:22:22.507
I don't. I just find it hard to
operate on the opposite assumption.

356
00:22:22.575 --> 00:22:25.511
And why are you so
afraid of making a mistake?

357
00:22:25.578 --> 00:22:29.037
Because I'm a doctor. Because
when we make mistakes. people die.

358
00:22:29.114 --> 00:22:31.106
Oh. come on.

359
00:22:33.118 --> 00:22:36.111
People used to have more
respect for cripples. you know.

360
00:22:39.124 --> 00:22:41.116
They didn't really.

361
00:22:44.797 --> 00:22:48.199
So how you feeling?
Much better. thanks.

362
00:22:48.267 --> 00:22:50.896
<i>Are you Dr. House? I
thought he was a he. but—</i>

363
00:22:50.970 --> 00:22:53.496
No.

364
00:22:53.572 --> 00:22:56.599
Don't eat too much. too fast.

365
00:22:56.675 --> 00:22:58.667
Thank him for me.

366
00:22:58.744 --> 00:23:01.270
Right.

367
00:23:12.491 --> 00:23:14.926
Should I discontinue
the treatment. boss?

368
00:23:14.994 --> 00:23:16.986
You got lucky.

369
00:23:20.366 --> 00:23:22.358
Cool. huh?

370
00:23:24.637 --> 00:23:26.572
<i>Okay. once again.</i>

371
00:23:26.639 --> 00:23:29.234
[Inhales. Exhales]

372
00:23:29.308 --> 00:23:31.243
Good.

373
00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:33.745
Am I ever gonna meet Dr. House?

374
00:23:33.812 --> 00:23:38.512
[Chuckles] Well. you might run
into him at the movies or on the bus.

375
00:23:38.584 --> 00:23:40.610
Is he a good man?

376
00:23:40.686 --> 00:23:44.350
He's a good doctor.

377
00:23:44.423 --> 00:23:46.756
Can you be one
without the other?

378
00:23:46.825 --> 00:23:50.626
Don't you have to care about
people? Caring is a good motivator.

379
00:23:51.864 --> 00:23:53.799
He's found something else.

380
00:23:56.001 --> 00:23:58.561
Feel this. both sides?
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

381
00:23:58.637 --> 00:24:02.631
Okay. squeeze.
Harder. All right.

382
00:24:02.708 --> 00:24:04.609
He's your friend. huh?

383
00:24:04.677 --> 00:24:06.805
Yeah.

384
00:24:06.879 --> 00:24:09.314
Does he care about you?

385
00:24:10.382 --> 00:24:12.613
I think so. You don't know?

386
00:24:13.686 --> 00:24:15.917
As Dr. House likes to
say. "Everybody lies."

387
00:24:17.189 --> 00:24:19.784
It's not what people
say. It's what they do.

388
00:24:23.295 --> 00:24:26.288
Yeah. He cares about me.

389
00:24:30.002 --> 00:24:31.994
<i>I can't see.</i>

390
00:24:34.707 --> 00:24:38.144
I can't... see.

391
00:24:40.646 --> 00:24:44.413
<i>[Monitor Beeping Rapidly]</i>

392
00:24:46.018 --> 00:24:47.919
A little help in here!

393
00:24:52.024 --> 00:24:55.517
[Sustained Tone]

394
00:25:01.467 --> 00:25:03.766
<i>Your chest will
be sore for a while.</i>

395
00:25:03.836 --> 00:25:06.806
We needed to shock you
to get your heart going.

396
00:25:09.308 --> 00:25:14.611
Okay. can you arrange
these to tell a story?

397
00:25:28.227 --> 00:25:30.162
<i>[Foreman] She couldn't
put them in order.</i>

398
00:25:30.229 --> 00:25:34.325
Could the damage have been caused
by a lack of oxygen during her seizure?

399
00:25:34.400 --> 00:25:38.235
No. I gave her the same test
five minutes later. She did just fine.

400
00:25:38.303 --> 00:25:41.831
The altered mental status is
intermittent. just like the verbal skills.

401
00:25:41.907 --> 00:25:43.842
So what now?

402
00:25:43.909 --> 00:25:46.970
Given the latest symptoms. it's clearly
growing deeper into the brain stem.

403
00:25:47.046 --> 00:25:49.413
Soon. she won't be able to walk.

404
00:25:49.481 --> 00:25:52.918
She'll go blind permanently. and
then the respiratory center will fail.

405
00:25:52.985 --> 00:25:54.920
How long do we have?

406
00:25:54.987 --> 00:25:57.866
If it's a tumor. we're talking a month
or two. If it's infectious. a few weeks.

407
00:25:57.890 --> 00:26:02.453
If it's vascular. that'll probably
be fastest of all. Maybe a week.

408
00:26:02.528 --> 00:26:04.656
We're gonna stop all treatment.

409
00:26:06.698 --> 00:26:09.377
I still think it's a tumor. I think
we should go back to the radiation.

410
00:26:09.401 --> 00:26:11.336
[Chase] She didn't
respond to the radiation.

411
00:26:11.403 --> 00:26:13.339
Well. maybe we didn't
see the effect until

412
00:26:13.363 --> 00:26:15.602
after we started steroids.
No. it's not a tumor.

413
00:26:15.674 --> 00:26:18.644
<i>Those steroids did something.
I just don't know what.</i>

414
00:26:18.710 --> 00:26:21.942
So we're just gonna do nothing?
We're just gonna watch her die?

415
00:26:22.014 --> 00:26:24.441
Yeah. we're gonna
watch her die. Specifically.

416
00:26:24.465 --> 00:26:26.543
we're gonna watch
how fast she's dying.

417
00:26:26.618 --> 00:26:30.214
<i>You just told us— Each
diagnosis has its own time frame.</i>

418
00:26:30.289 --> 00:26:33.487
When we see how fast it's
killing her. we'll know what it is.

419
00:26:33.559 --> 00:26:36.495
And by then. maybe there's
nothing we can do about it.

420
00:26:36.562 --> 00:26:38.622
<i>There's got to be
something we can do.</i>

421
00:26:38.697 --> 00:26:40.563
Something better
than watching her die.

422
00:26:40.632 --> 00:26:43.124
Well. I got nothing.

423
00:26:43.202 --> 00:26:45.194
How about you?

424
00:26:49.641 --> 00:26:51.576
Bastard.

425
00:26:51.643 --> 00:26:54.579
Oh. Cameron. I need you for
a couple of hours. What's up?

426
00:26:54.646 --> 00:26:56.632
When you break into
someone's house. it's better

427
00:26:56.656 --> 00:26:58.583
to have a white chick
with you. Adler's house?

428
00:26:58.650 --> 00:27:00.799
Why don't we just ask
her for her keys? For all we

429
00:27:00.823 --> 00:27:03.213
know. she'll be running a
meth lab out of her basement.

430
00:27:03.288 --> 00:27:05.280
I'm tired a lot.

431
00:27:06.592 --> 00:27:10.154
Any other reason why you think you
might have chronic fatigue syndrome?

432
00:27:10.229 --> 00:27:12.255
It's kind of the
definition. isn't it?

433
00:27:12.331 --> 00:27:14.357
It's kind of the
definition of getting older.

434
00:27:14.433 --> 00:27:17.001
I had a couple headaches
last month. a mild fever.

435
00:27:17.025 --> 00:27:20.031
Sometimes I can't sleep. and
I have trouble concentrating.

436
00:27:20.105 --> 00:27:23.200
Apparently not while researching
this stuff on the Internet.

437
00:27:23.275 --> 00:27:27.076
I was thinking it also
might be fibromyalgia.

438
00:27:29.348 --> 00:27:31.283
Excellent diagnosis.

439
00:27:31.350 --> 00:27:33.251
Is there anything for that?

440
00:27:33.318 --> 00:27:39.280
[Sighs] You know. I
think there just might be.

441
00:27:39.358 --> 00:27:43.261
I need 36 Vicodin
and change for a dollar.

442
00:28:05.884 --> 00:28:07.648
Exam room two.

443
00:28:10.489 --> 00:28:12.424
House doesn't
believe in pretense.

444
00:28:12.491 --> 00:28:15.791
Figures life's too short and too
painful. So he just says what he thinks.

445
00:28:17.095 --> 00:28:19.326
Nothing interesting
in the garbage.

446
00:28:19.398 --> 00:28:22.163
"I say what I think" is just another
way of saying "I'm an assho"...

447
00:28:24.570 --> 00:28:27.506
Well. if you wanted to be judged
for your medical prowess only.

448
00:28:27.573 --> 00:28:30.008
maybe you shouldn't have
broken into someone's home.

449
00:28:30.075 --> 00:28:32.067
I was 16.

450
00:28:33.612 --> 00:28:36.605
Don't know about ticks. but
her dog's definitely got fleas.

451
00:28:39.251 --> 00:28:42.346
I managed to make it to
17 without a criminal record.

452
00:28:45.424 --> 00:28:47.359
Yeah?

453
00:28:47.426 --> 00:28:51.363
Well. you obviously didn't
grow up in my neighborhood.

454
00:28:51.430 --> 00:28:54.867
That's right. You stole a loaf of bread
to feed your starving family. Right?

455
00:28:54.933 --> 00:28:56.868
You always eat during break-ins?

456
00:28:56.935 --> 00:29:00.372
Am I supposed to respect their food
more than I respect their DVD players?

457
00:29:00.439 --> 00:29:01.873
You want some? <i>No.</i>

458
00:29:01.940 --> 00:29:04.307
<i>You gonna go
hungry until she dies?</i>

459
00:29:04.376 --> 00:29:05.674
No. <i>You know what?</i>

460
00:29:05.744 --> 00:29:08.976
After centuries of slavery.
decades of civil rights marches...

461
00:29:09.047 --> 00:29:13.951
and. more significantly. living like a
monk. never getting less than a 4.0 G.P.A..

462
00:29:14.019 --> 00:29:16.272
you don't think it's kind
of disgusting I get one of

463
00:29:16.296 --> 00:29:18.616
the top jobs in the country
because I'm a delinquent?

464
00:29:19.925 --> 00:29:22.451
We'll eat. then we'll
tear up the carpet.

465
00:29:24.763 --> 00:29:26.698
You went to Hopkins. right?

466
00:29:26.765 --> 00:29:28.666
Yep.

467
00:29:28.734 --> 00:29:32.000
So you went to a better school than I
did. You got better grades than I did.

468
00:29:32.070 --> 00:29:35.006
[Laughs] So how
did you get the job?

469
00:29:35.073 --> 00:29:37.474
You stab a guy in a bar fight?

470
00:29:45.117 --> 00:29:47.052
<i>[Foreman] Nothing.</i>

471
00:29:47.119 --> 00:29:50.487
It's not a tumor. She's
getting worse too fast.

472
00:29:50.555 --> 00:29:54.014
<i>- She can't stand up.</i>
- No toxins? No medications?

473
00:29:54.092 --> 00:29:55.754
Nothing that would
explain these symptoms.

474
00:29:55.827 --> 00:29:57.819
Family history of
neurological problems?

475
00:29:57.896 --> 00:30:00.229
Not that I could tell from
her underwear drawer.

476
00:30:00.299 --> 00:30:02.734
<i>You said "nothing that would
explain these symptoms."</i>

477
00:30:02.801 --> 00:30:05.430
What did you find that <i>doesn't</i>
explain these symptoms?

478
00:30:06.772 --> 00:30:10.766
Dr. Wilson convinced you to treat
this patient under false pretenses.

479
00:30:10.842 --> 00:30:12.936
<i>Adler's not his cousin.</i>

480
00:30:14.112 --> 00:30:16.090
That's ridiculous. Ask her
yourself. Can we get ba...

481
00:30:16.114 --> 00:30:18.606
- She's not Jewish.
- Rachel Adler's not Jewish?

482
00:30:18.684 --> 00:30:22.177
- I had ham at her apartment.
- [Laughs]

483
00:30:22.254 --> 00:30:24.281
Dr. Foreman. a lot of
Jews have non-Jewish

484
00:30:24.305 --> 00:30:26.453
relatives. and most of
us don't keep kosher.

485
00:30:26.525 --> 00:30:28.249
<i>I can see getting through
high school without</i>

486
00:30:28.273 --> 00:30:30.138
<i>learning a thing about
Jews. but medical school?</i>

487
00:30:30.162 --> 00:30:33.599
Okay. maybe she’s Jewish. but
she's definitely not your cousin.

488
00:30:33.665 --> 00:30:36.032
<i>Really? This guy is— [Stammers]</i>

489
00:30:36.101 --> 00:30:39.765
<i>You don't even know her name. You
called her Rachel. Her name is Rebecca.</i>

490
00:30:40.906 --> 00:30:43.068
Yes. Yes. her name is Rebecca.

491
00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:47.109
I-I call her Rachel.

492
00:30:47.179 --> 00:30:49.546
You idiot! [Stammering]
Listen. he's...

493
00:30:49.614 --> 00:30:51.606
Not you. Him.

494
00:30:51.683 --> 00:30:55.450
<i>- You said you didn't find anything.</i>
- Everything I found was in my...

495
00:30:55.520 --> 00:30:57.921
- You found ham.
- So?

496
00:30:57.989 --> 00:31:00.322
Where there's ham. there's pork.

497
00:31:00.392 --> 00:31:03.226
Where there's pork.
there's neurocysticercosis.

498
00:31:03.295 --> 00:31:05.821
Tapeworm? You think
she's got a worm in her brain?

499
00:31:05.897 --> 00:31:08.476
It fits. Could have been living there
for years. Never occurred to me that...

500
00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:10.423
Millions of people eat
ham every day. It's quite

501
00:31:10.447 --> 00:31:12.232
a leap to think that's
she's got a tapeworm.

502
00:31:12.304 --> 00:31:14.800
Okay. Mr. Neurologist.
what happens when you

503
00:31:14.824 --> 00:31:17.402
give steroids to a person
who has a tapeworm?

504
00:31:17.476 --> 00:31:21.140
<i>They— They get a little better.
and— and then they get worse.</i>

505
00:31:23.682 --> 00:31:26.777
Just like Rebecca Adler did.

506
00:31:36.461 --> 00:31:39.989
In a typical case. if you
don't cook pork well enough.

507
00:31:40.065 --> 00:31:43.558
<i>you digest live tapeworm larvae.</i>

508
00:31:43.635 --> 00:31:45.866
<i>They've got these little hooks.</i>

509
00:31:45.937 --> 00:31:48.316
they grab onto your bowel. they
live. they grow up. they reproduce.

510
00:31:48.340 --> 00:31:52.710
Reproduce? There's only one
lesion. and it's nowhere near her bowel.

511
00:31:52.778 --> 00:31:55.145
That's because this
is not a typical case.

512
00:31:55.213 --> 00:31:59.173
Tapeworm can produce
20.000 to 30.000 eggs a day.

513
00:31:59.251 --> 00:32:01.186
<i>Guess where they
go? [Foreman] Out.</i>

514
00:32:01.253 --> 00:32:03.188
<i>Not all of them.</i>

515
00:32:03.255 --> 00:32:05.962
<i>Unlike the larvae. the
egg can pass right through</i>

516
00:32:05.986 --> 00:32:08.717
<i>the walls of the intestines
into the bloodstream.</i>

517
00:32:08.794 --> 00:32:11.059
<i>And where does the bloodstream
go? [Cameron] Everywhere.</i>

518
00:32:11.129 --> 00:32:15.328
As long as it's healthy. the immune
system doesn't even know it's there.

519
00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:17.992
<i>The worm builds a wall.
uses secretions to shut down</i>

520
00:32:18.016 --> 00:32:20.532
<i>the body's immune
response and control fluid flow.</i>

521
00:32:20.605 --> 00:32:23.404
It's really very beautiful.

522
00:32:23.475 --> 00:32:26.035
As long as it's healthy.
So what do we do?

523
00:32:26.111 --> 00:32:29.047
Call a vet. nurse the
little guy back to health?

524
00:32:29.114 --> 00:32:32.050
It's too late for
that. It's dying.

525
00:32:32.117 --> 00:32:36.521
<i>And as it dies. this parasite loses the
ability to control the host's defenses.</i>

526
00:32:36.588 --> 00:32:40.582
<i>The immune system wakes up. attacks
the worm. and everything starts to swell.</i>

527
00:32:40.659 --> 00:32:43.686
<i>And that is very
bad for the brain.</i>

528
00:32:43.762 --> 00:32:46.391
<i>It could still be a
hundred other things.</i>

529
00:32:46.465 --> 00:32:48.661
<i>The eosinophil count was normal.</i>

530
00:32:48.733 --> 00:32:51.567
- It's only abnormal in 30% of cases.
- Proving nothing.

531
00:32:51.636 --> 00:32:56.768
No. no. no. no. It— Don't you see? It
fits. It's perfect. It explains everything.

532
00:32:56.842 --> 00:32:59.676
- But it proves nothing.
- I can prove it by treating it.

533
00:32:59.744 --> 00:33:01.713
No. you can't.

534
00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:05.376
I was just with her. She doesn't
want any more treatments.

535
00:33:05.450 --> 00:33:08.943
She doesn't want any more experiments.
She wants to go home and die.

536
00:33:19.564 --> 00:33:22.500
<i>[Rain Falling]</i>

537
00:33:22.567 --> 00:33:25.059
<i>[Thunder Rumbling]</i>

538
00:33:31.343 --> 00:33:33.505
Would you excuse us. please?

539
00:33:39.050 --> 00:33:40.746
I'm Dr. House.

540
00:33:40.819 --> 00:33:43.379
It's good to meet you.

541
00:33:47.392 --> 00:33:49.759
You're being an
idiot. [Clears Throat]

542
00:33:54.432 --> 00:33:56.924
You have a
tapeworm in your brain.

543
00:33:58.169 --> 00:34:01.867
It's not pleasant. but if we don't do
anything. you'll be dead by the weekend.

544
00:34:01.940 --> 00:34:04.239
Have you actually seen the worm?

545
00:34:04.309 --> 00:34:07.279
When you're all better.
I'll show you my diplomas.

546
00:34:07.345 --> 00:34:10.110
You were sure I
had vasculitis too.

547
00:34:10.181 --> 00:34:13.117
Now I can't walk and
I'm wearing a diaper.

548
00:34:13.184 --> 00:34:15.210
What's this treatment
gonna do for me?

549
00:34:15.287 --> 00:34:18.689
I'm not talking about a
treatment. I'm talking about a cure.

550
00:34:18.757 --> 00:34:21.750
But because I might be
wrong. you want to die.

551
00:34:23.194 --> 00:34:25.186
What made you a cripple?

552
00:34:29.100 --> 00:34:31.092
I had an infarction.

553
00:34:31.169 --> 00:34:33.604
A heart attack?

554
00:34:33.672 --> 00:34:36.107
It's what happens when
blood flow is obstructed.

555
00:34:36.174 --> 00:34:37.690
If it's in the heart.
it's a heart attack. If

556
00:34:37.714 --> 00:34:39.253
it's in the lungs. it's a
pulmonary embolism.

557
00:34:39.277 --> 00:34:42.213
If it's in the brain. it's a stroke.
I had it in my thigh muscles.

558
00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:44.875
Wasn't there something
they could do?

559
00:34:44.950 --> 00:34:48.114
There was plenty they could do.
if they'd made the right diagnosis.

560
00:34:48.186 --> 00:34:51.088
<i>But the only symptom was pain.</i>

561
00:34:52.290 --> 00:34:55.283
Not many people get to
experience muscle death.

562
00:34:55.360 --> 00:34:57.056
Did you think you were dying?

563
00:34:57.128 --> 00:34:59.723
I hoped I was dying.

564
00:35:00.865 --> 00:35:03.801
So you hide in your office.
refuse to see patients...

565
00:35:03.868 --> 00:35:07.498
because you don't like
the way people look at you.

566
00:35:07.572 --> 00:35:11.771
You feel cheated by life. so now
you're gonna get even with the world.

567
00:35:11.843 --> 00:35:14.779
But you want me to fight this.

568
00:35:14.846 --> 00:35:16.781
Why?

569
00:35:16.848 --> 00:35:19.818
What makes you think I'm
so much better than you?

570
00:35:19.884 --> 00:35:22.979
What. you're scared
you'll turn into me?

571
00:35:23.054 --> 00:35:26.320
I just want to die
with a little dignity.

572
00:35:26.391 --> 00:35:28.690
There's no such thing.

573
00:35:28.760 --> 00:35:32.026
Our bodies break down. Sometimes when
we're 90. Sometimes before we're even born.

574
00:35:32.097 --> 00:35:35.033
But it always happens. and
there's never any dignity in it.

575
00:35:35.100 --> 00:35:40.004
I don't care if you can walk. see. wipe
your own ass. It's always ugly. Always.

576
00:35:44.042 --> 00:35:47.035
We can live with dignity.
We can't die with it.

577
00:36:04.863 --> 00:36:06.855
No treatment.

578
00:36:07.866 --> 00:36:11.200
Maybe we can get a court
order. uh. override her wishes.

579
00:36:11.269 --> 00:36:14.205
claim she doesn't have the
capacity to make this decision.

580
00:36:14.272 --> 00:36:16.207
But she does.

581
00:36:16.274 --> 00:36:19.210
<i>But we could claim that the illness
made her mentally incompetent. right?</i>

582
00:36:19.277 --> 00:36:21.712
A pretty common result.
That didn't happen here.

583
00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:25.547
<i>He's not gonna do it. She's
not just a file to him anymore.</i>

584
00:36:25.617 --> 00:36:27.552
He respects her.

585
00:36:27.619 --> 00:36:30.316
So because you respect
her. you're going to let her die?

586
00:36:32.257 --> 00:36:35.091
I solved the case.
My work is done.

587
00:36:37.362 --> 00:36:39.228
<i>Patients always want proof.</i>

588
00:36:39.297 --> 00:36:41.493
We're not making cars here.

589
00:36:41.566 --> 00:36:43.933
We don't give guarantees.

590
00:36:45.603 --> 00:36:47.595
I think we can
prove it's a worm.

591
00:36:49.174 --> 00:36:51.643
It's noninvasive. It's safe.

592
00:36:51.710 --> 00:36:54.874
I'm not completely sure. but— Yeah.
yeah. yeah. What's the damn idea?

593
00:36:54.946 --> 00:36:57.381
Have you ever seen a
worm under an X-ray?

594
00:36:57.449 --> 00:37:00.385
A regular. old. no-contrast.
hundred-year-old-technology X-ray?

595
00:37:00.452 --> 00:37:04.583
They light up like shotgun
pellets. just like on a contrast M.R.I.

596
00:37:04.656 --> 00:37:07.956
Which is the same thing as a CT
scan. which we did. which proved nothing.

597
00:37:08.026 --> 00:37:10.962
The worm's cyst is the same
density as the cerebrospinal fluid.

598
00:37:11.029 --> 00:37:13.589
We're not gonna see
anything in her head.

599
00:37:13.665 --> 00:37:17.124
But Chase is right. He's
right. We should X-ray her.

600
00:37:17.202 --> 00:37:20.138
But we don't X-ray her
brain. We X-ray her leg.

601
00:37:20.205 --> 00:37:22.589
Worms love thigh muscle.
If she's got one in her

602
00:37:22.613 --> 00:37:24.870
head. I guarantee you
there's one in her leg.

603
00:37:38.323 --> 00:37:40.224
Hold still. Rebecca.

604
00:37:48.867 --> 00:37:51.234
This here...

605
00:37:51.302 --> 00:37:53.237
is a worm larva.

606
00:37:53.304 --> 00:37:55.899
So. if it's in my
leg. it's in my brain?

607
00:37:55.974 --> 00:37:59.240
Are you looking for a guarantee?

608
00:37:59.310 --> 00:38:01.836
It's there. Probably
been there six to 10 years.

609
00:38:01.913 --> 00:38:05.179
- Do I have more?
- Probably.

610
00:38:06.651 --> 00:38:08.677
It's good news.

611
00:38:08.753 --> 00:38:11.746
- What do we do now?
- Now we get you better.

612
00:38:14.159 --> 00:38:16.151
Albendazole.

613
00:38:17.929 --> 00:38:22.264
- Two pills?
<i>- Yeah. Every day.</i>
<i>for at least a month. with a meal.</i>

614
00:38:22.333 --> 00:38:24.893
- Two pills?
- Yeah.

615
00:38:24.969 --> 00:38:27.437
Possible side effects
include abdominal

616
00:38:27.461 --> 00:38:30.272
pain. nausea. headaches.
dizziness. fever...

617
00:38:30.341 --> 00:38:32.276
and hair loss.

618
00:38:32.343 --> 00:38:35.543
We'll probably make you keep taking the
pills even if you get every one of those.

619
00:38:54.566 --> 00:38:56.797
Why did you hire me?

620
00:38:57.802 --> 00:39:00.614
- Does it matter?
- Kinda hard to work for a guy
who doesn't respect you.

621
00:39:00.638 --> 00:39:02.664
- Why?
- Is that rhetorical?

622
00:39:02.740 --> 00:39:05.335
No. It just seems that way
'cause you can't think of an answer.

623
00:39:07.078 --> 00:39:09.343
Does it make a
difference what I think?

624
00:39:09.414 --> 00:39:14.409
I'm a jerk. The only thing that matters
is what <i>you</i> think. Can you do the job?

625
00:39:14.485 --> 00:39:17.785
You hired a black guy because
he had a juvenile record. No.

626
00:39:17.856 --> 00:39:19.791
It wasn't a racial thing.

627
00:39:19.858 --> 00:39:21.793
I didn't see a black guy.

628
00:39:21.860 --> 00:39:24.022
I just saw a doctor...

629
00:39:24.095 --> 00:39:26.030
with a juvenile record.

630
00:39:26.097 --> 00:39:29.033
I hired Chase 'cause his
dad made a phone call.

631
00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:31.228
I hired you...

632
00:39:31.302 --> 00:39:33.430
because you are
extremely pretty.

633
00:39:33.504 --> 00:39:38.442
You hired me to get into my pants? I
can't believe that that would shock you.

634
00:39:38.509 --> 00:39:40.444
It's also not what I said.

635
00:39:40.511 --> 00:39:42.707
No. I hired you
because you look good.

636
00:39:42.780 --> 00:39:45.272
It's like having a nice
piece of art in the lobby.

637
00:39:45.350 --> 00:39:47.785
- I was in the top of my class.
- But not <i>the</i> top.

638
00:39:47.852 --> 00:39:51.345
I did an internship at the Mayo Clinic.
Yeah. You were a very good applicant.

639
00:39:51.422 --> 00:39:54.358
But not the best. Would
that upset you? Really?

640
00:39:54.425 --> 00:39:56.647
To think that you were hired
because of some genetic gift

641
00:39:56.671 --> 00:39:58.839
of beauty instead of some
genetic gift of intelligence?

642
00:39:58.863 --> 00:40:01.298
I worked very hard
to get where I am.

643
00:40:01.366 --> 00:40:03.301
But you didn't have to.

644
00:40:03.368 --> 00:40:05.304
People choose the
paths that gain them the

645
00:40:05.328 --> 00:40:07.567
greatest rewards for
the least amount of effort.

646
00:40:07.639 --> 00:40:11.440
That's a law of nature. and you
defied it. That's why I hired you.

647
00:40:11.509 --> 00:40:14.445
<i>You could have married rich.
You could have been a model.</i>

648
00:40:14.512 --> 00:40:18.040
<i>You could have just shown up and people
would have given you stuff. Lots of stuff.</i>

649
00:40:18.116 --> 00:40:21.484
But you didn't. You worked
your stunning little ass off.

650
00:40:21.552 --> 00:40:23.987
Am I supposed to be flattered?

651
00:40:24.055 --> 00:40:26.490
Gorgeous women do
not go to medical school...

652
00:40:26.557 --> 00:40:29.550
unless they're as damaged
as they are beautiful.

653
00:40:29.627 --> 00:40:31.562
Were you abused
by a family member?

654
00:40:31.629 --> 00:40:33.427
- No.
- Sexually assaulted?

655
00:40:33.498 --> 00:40:35.626
No!

656
00:40:35.700 --> 00:40:37.566
But you are damaged. aren't you?

657
00:40:39.037 --> 00:40:41.336
<i>♪♪ [Pager]</i>

658
00:40:41.406 --> 00:40:45.173
[Exhales] I have to go.

659
00:40:49.314 --> 00:40:51.010
I followed her.

660
00:40:51.082 --> 00:40:55.486
- Oh.
- I couldn't stop thinking
about what that doctor said.

661
00:40:55.553 --> 00:40:57.516
I told you not to listen
to him. He's an idiot.

662
00:40:57.540 --> 00:40:58.540
I was orange!

663
00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:02.792
- I don't want to know what you found out.
- You don't care?

664
00:41:02.860 --> 00:41:04.795
I'm your doctor.

665
00:41:04.862 --> 00:41:07.798
You've been good to me and good
to this hospital. Of course I care.

666
00:41:07.865 --> 00:41:11.324
<i>But I don't see how this
conversation can end well for me.</i>

667
00:41:11.402 --> 00:41:14.668
Either your wife is having an
affair. or she's not having an affair.

668
00:41:14.739 --> 00:41:17.675
and you have come here because
you rightly think I should fire him.

669
00:41:17.742 --> 00:41:21.804
But I can't. Even if it
costs me your money.

670
00:41:21.879 --> 00:41:25.213
The son of a bitch is
the best doctor we have.

671
00:41:30.788 --> 00:41:32.723
Feeling any better?

672
00:41:32.790 --> 00:41:34.725
I can't complain.

673
00:41:34.792 --> 00:41:37.125
As you know. the
hospital has certain rules.

674
00:41:37.195 --> 00:41:41.064
And as you also know.
we tend to ignore them.

675
00:41:41.132 --> 00:41:43.610
But I think this one's gonna be a
little obvious unless we get your help.

676
00:41:43.634 --> 00:41:47.002
<i>If anyone asks. you have 1
1 daughters and five sons.</i>

677
00:41:47.071 --> 00:41:50.803
- Hi! Look who's here!
- [Children Chattering]

678
00:41:50.875 --> 00:41:54.710
It's so good to see
you guys. I missed you.

679
00:41:55.480 --> 00:41:57.381
Is this for me?

680
00:41:57.448 --> 00:41:59.508
<i>It's beautiful.</i>

681
00:42:01.919 --> 00:42:04.650
<i>Oh. I love you guys.</i>

682
00:42:04.722 --> 00:42:07.692
I wanted to thank Dr. House.
but he never visited again.

683
00:42:07.759 --> 00:42:10.092
He cured you.
You didn't cure him.

684
00:42:11.229 --> 00:42:16.258
Okay. I want a hug and a kiss from every
single one of you! Get up here right now!

685
00:42:18.302 --> 00:42:21.238
- [Woman] There.
- [Man] Hold on.

686
00:42:21.305 --> 00:42:23.536
<i>[Woman] She's converted.</i>

687
00:42:23.608 --> 00:42:25.543
[Sniffs]

688
00:42:25.610 --> 00:42:28.239
You said she was your cousin.

689
00:42:28.312 --> 00:42:30.247
Why would you lie?

690
00:42:30.314 --> 00:42:33.113
It got you to take the case.

691
00:42:34.118 --> 00:42:37.953
You lied to a friend to save a stranger.
You don't think that's kind of screwed up?

692
00:42:38.022 --> 00:42:39.786
You've never lied to me?

693
00:42:39.857 --> 00:42:42.383
I never lie.

694
00:42:42.460 --> 00:42:45.020
Oh. Right.

695
00:42:46.330 --> 00:42:49.027
- [Man] Why do we do this?
- [Woman] Because we're doctors.

696
00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:51.433
If we make mistakes. people die.

697
00:42:53.471 --> 00:42:56.100
<i>- [Knock On Door]</i>
- Dr. House?

698
00:42:56.174 --> 00:42:58.200
<i>You have a patient.</i>

699
00:43:02.713 --> 00:43:06.047
- [Sighs]
- He says he needs a refill.

700
00:43:09.187 --> 00:43:11.213
Got change for a dollar?

701
00:43:55.266 --> 00:43:56.529
That's some bad hat. Harry.

701
